    {
      "turn_number": 32,
      "role": "persona",
      "type": "response",
      "text": "Yes — there is one more thing that keeps coming back to me. I wish someone had asked me to tell my story, not just check boxes. When they asked about my stomach pain, I wanted them to listen to how my gut had been hurting for years, how pregnancy made it worse. I know my body — I lived with painful cycles and pelvic problems and I wanted a doctor to take that seriously, not move on because my chart said \"low risk.\"\n\nI also want care that speaks my language — not just an interpreter on the phone but someone who slows down, uses plain words, and looks at me like I am a whole person. The blank line where \"marital status\" goes made me feel judged; small things like that matter. And please, help with the practical parts: paperwork for work, referrals, a support group with other immigrant moms. I am proud of my strength — I want providers to see that, to trust me when I say something hurts or feels wrong. That would have made all the difference. Thank you for listening.",
      "responding_to_question_id": null,
      "input_tokens": 1302,
      "output_tokens": 414
    }
